<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<p>The model for a 2D materials on a substrate is shown in 
 <xref ref-type="fig" rid="nanomaterials-09-00978-f001">Figure 1</xref>, where the substrate of 
 <italic>M</italic> atoms is treated as a thermal bath at temperature 
 <italic>T</italic>. For calculations of the PF for the 2D materials of 
 <italic>N</italic> atoms, the total potential is expressed as: 
 <disp-formula id="FD1-nanomaterials-09-00978">
  <label>(1)</label>
  <math id="mm2">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>U</mi>
     <mrow>
      <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
      <mrow>
       <msup>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mrow>
         <mn>3</mn>
         <mi>N</mi>
        </mrow>
       </msup>
       <mo>,</mo>
       <msup>
        <mi>X</mi>
        <mrow>
         <mn>3</mn>
         <mi>M</mi>
        </mrow>
       </msup>
      </mrow>
      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
     </mrow>
     <mo>=</mo>
     <msub>
      <mi>U</mi>
      <mrow>
       <mn>2</mn>
       <mi>D</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
     <mrow>
      <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
      <mrow>
       <msup>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mrow>
         <mn>3</mn>
         <mi>N</mi>
        </mrow>
       </msup>
      </mrow>
      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
     </mrow>
     <mo>+</mo>
     <mi>V</mi>
     <mrow>
      <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
      <mrow>
       <msup>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mrow>
         <mn>3</mn>
         <mi>N</mi>
        </mrow>
       </msup>
       <mo>,</mo>
       <msup>
        <mi>X</mi>
        <mrow>
         <mn>3</mn>
         <mi>M</mi>
        </mrow>
       </msup>
      </mrow>
      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
     </mrow>
     <mo>,</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula> where 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm3">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi>U</mi>
      <mrow>
       <mn>2</mn>
       <mi>D</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is the potential energy of the 2D material with the coordinates of the atoms denoted by 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm4">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msup>
      <mi>x</mi>
      <mrow>
       <mn>3</mn>
       <mi>N</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msup>
     <mrow>
      <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
      <mrow>
       <msub>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mn>1</mn>
       </msub>
       <mo>,</mo>
       <msub>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mn>2</mn>
       </msub>
       <mo>…</mo>
       <msub>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mrow>
         <mn>3</mn>
         <mi>N</mi>
        </mrow>
       </msub>
      </mrow>
      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
     </mrow>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> and 
 <italic>V</italic> is the interaction potential between the 2D material and the substrate with its atoms denoted by 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm5">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msup>
      <mi>X</mi>
      <mrow>
       <mn>3</mn>
       <mi>M</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msup>
     <mrow>
      <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
      <mrow>
       <msub>
        <mi>X</mi>
        <mn>1</mn>
       </msub>
       <mo>,</mo>
       <msub>
        <mi>X</mi>
        <mn>2</mn>
       </msub>
       <mo>…</mo>
       <msub>
        <mi>X</mi>
        <mrow>
         <mn>3</mn>
         <mi>M</mi>
        </mrow>
       </msub>
      </mrow>
      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
     </mrow>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. 
</p>
